d fads within the profession that have weakened the fundamentals of the field. In looking for a way forward, Lukacs explores the critical relationships between history and literature, including ways in which novelists have contributed to historical understanding. Through this startling and enlightening work, readers will understand Lukacs's assertion that "everything has its history, including history" and that history itself has a future, since everything we know comes from the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistorians. 0aHistoriographyxHistory. 0aHistoriographyxPhilosophy. 0aHistoryxMethodology. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030016956040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030017513440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300175134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300175134/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY